    "### Employer Project: Kite"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f7e40593",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Geographic, Courier, and Cost Saving Analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1d4aa2fd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this Jupyter Notebook we have looked to analyse Kite data in order to help solve Kite's business problem of reducing costs by 20% around its Coventry distribution centre. Following data cleaning, the first step was to carry out geographic analysis which entailed finding postcode clusters within the 50-mile radius around the Coventry distribution centre. We then looked to see whether we should replace all couriers that Kite uses, or whether we should only investigate replacing some of them. Once this was complete, we then created a truck allocation model that computed the optimal truck number and size needed for each cluster based on a certain number of pallets. Our truck analysis used this model to compute two options for trucks within the clusters, minimum and median daily pallets. In order to compare these options, we created a function that calculated the cost savings that each could offer to Kite."
   ]
  },

    "### 1. Geographic Analysis: Clustering. "
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We decided to investiagte clusters of orders within the 50-mile radius around the Coventry distribution centre. Identifying these clusters meant that we could then assign different trucks to different areas, and therefore, have tailored delivery strategies for different areas. It also meant that we could, if Kite wanted to, suggest a phased approach to bringing in more in-house deliveries ie. start with a pilot cluster and then expand in-house capabilities to other clusters, and so on."
   ]
  },

    "# Merge the long-lat and miles50_coventry DataFrames into a new one.\n",
    "# Carry out a left join to get a latitude and longitiude for each postcode.\n",

    "                right_on = 'outcode',\n",
    "                how = 'left')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Check for missing values in longitude and latitude.\n",
    "data.isnull().sum()"

    "#### Determine the Number of Clusters."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "bbc3bf63",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a variable to store the longitude and latitude of the postcodes.\n",
    "# This is what we will use to carry out our cluster analysis.\n",
    "b = data[['longitude','latitude']]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "ecd39e6b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1600x800 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Determine the number of clusters: Elbow method.\n",
    "# Create Elbow chart to decide on the optimal number of clusters.\n",
    "ss = []\n",
    "for i in range(1, 11):\n",
    "    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i,\n",
    "                    init='k-means++',\n",
    "                    max_iter=500,\n",
    "                    n_init=10,\n",
    "                    random_state=42)\n",
    "    kmeans.fit(b)\n",
    "    ss.append(kmeans.inertia_)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(range(1, 11),\n",
    "         ss,\n",
    "         marker='o')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add titles and labels.\n",
    "plt.title(\"The Elbow Method\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Number of clusters\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Sum of Squared Distances\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Remove gridlines.\n",
    "plt.grid(False)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set x-axis tick labels to show every 1.\n",
    "plt.xticks(range(1, 11))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Save the chart.\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "filename = 'The Elbow Method.png'\n",
    "plt.savefig(filename)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show the plot.\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {

    "# Determine the number of clusters: Silhouette method.\n",
    "# Create Silhouette chart to decide on the optimal number of clusters.\n",
    "sil = []\n",
    "kmax = 10\n",
    "\n",
    "for k in range(2, kmax+1):\n",
    "    kmeans_s = KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(b)\n",
    "    labels = kmeans_s.labels_\n",
    "    sil.append(silhouette_score(b, labels, metric='euclidean'))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the silhouette method.\n",
    "plt.plot(range(2, kmax+1), sil, marker='o')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add title and labels.\n",
    "plt.title(\"The Silhouette Method\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Number of clusters\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Silhouette coefficient\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Remove gridlines.\n",
    "plt.grid(False)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Save the chart.\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "filename = 'The Silhouette Method.png'\n",
    "plt.savefig(filename)\n",
    "\n",
    "# View the output.\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

    "Our next step was to identify the trucks that Kite should acquire to carry out in-house deliveries. We decided to use number of pallets to inform what truck is needed in each cluster. To do this, we created a function, which essentially takes a given number of pallets and selects the smallest truck they can fit into, preferring one large truck over multiple smaller trucks as this is more cost-effective. "
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "82468a3b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We then refined our function to be able to allocate a maximum of two trucks to a cluster. This can be seen below and is the one we used for our final analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "id": "bf8bc779",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a function to allocate trucks to each cluster \n",
    "# based on the number of pallets needed to be delivered. \n",
    "\n",
    "def truck_allocation(pallets):\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Define the maximum pallet capacity of each type of truck and truck combination.\n",
    "    pallet_capacity_3_5_tonne_van = 2\n",
    "    pallet_capacity_7_5_tonne_LGV = 14\n",
    "    pallet_capacity_18_tonne_HGV = 24\n",
    "    pallet_capacity_18_3_5_tonne_trucks = 26\n",
    "    pallet_capacity_7_5_7_5_tonne_trucks = 28\n",
    "    pallet_capacity_18_7_5_tonne_trucks = 38\n",
    "    pallet_capacity_18_18_tonne_trucks = 48\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Create a DataFrame to store the truck type and number of trucks needed for each cluster.\n",
    "    df_trucks_needed = pd.DataFrame(index = pallets.index)\n",
    "    # Add columns to store the information needed.\n",
    "    df_trucks_needed['Pallets'] = pallets\n",
    "    df_trucks_needed['3.5-tonne Van (2)'] = 0\n",
    "    df_trucks_needed['7.5-tonne LGV (14)'] = 0\n",
    "    df_trucks_needed['18-tonne HGV (24)'] = 0\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Use a for loop to determine the truck type \n",
    "    # needed for the number of pallets in each cluster.\n",
    "    for cluster in df_trucks_needed.index:\n",
    "    \n",
    "        # Identify the pallets needed for that cluster. \n",
    "        pallets_needed = df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, 'Pallets']\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Check if the pallets needed can fit into a 3.5-tonne van.\n",
    "        if pallets_needed <= pallet_capacity_3_5_tonne_van:        \n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '3.5-tonne Van (2)'] = 1\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # If not, can they fit into a 7.5-tonne LGV.\n",
    "        elif pallet_capacity_3_5_tonne_van < pallets_needed <= \\\n",
    "        pallet_capacity_7_5_tonne_LGV:\n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '7.5-tonne LGV (14)'] = 1\n",
    "    \n",
    "        # If not, can they fit into an 18-tonne HGV.\n",
    "        elif pallet_capacity_7_5_tonne_LGV < pallets_needed <= \\\n",
    "        pallet_capacity_18_tonne_HGV:\n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '18-tonne HGV (24)'] = 1\n",
    "            \n",
    "        # If not, can they fit into an 18-tonne HGV and a 3.5-tonne van.\n",
    "        elif pallet_capacity_18_tonne_HGV < pallets_needed <= \\\n",
    "        pallet_capacity_18_3_5_tonne_trucks:\n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '18-tonne HGV (24)'] = 1\n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '3.5-tonne Van (2)'] = 1\n",
    "            \n",
    "        # If not, can they fit into two 7.5-tonne LGVs.\n",
    "        elif pallet_capacity_18_3_5_tonne_trucks < pallets_needed <= \\\n",
    "        pallet_capacity_7_5_7_5_tonne_trucks:\n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '7.5-tonne LGV (14)'] = 2\n",
    "            \n",
    "        # If not, can they fit into an 18-tonne HGV and a 7.5-tonne LGV.\n",
    "        elif pallet_capacity_7_5_7_5_tonne_trucks < pallets_needed <= \\\n",
    "        pallet_capacity_18_7_5_tonne_trucks:\n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '18-tonne HGV (24)'] = 1\n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '7.5-tonne LGV (14)'] = 1\n",
    "            \n",
    "        # If not, can they fit into two 18-tonne HGVs.\n",
    "        elif pallet_capacity_18_7_5_tonne_trucks < pallets_needed <= \\\n",
    "        pallet_capacity_18_18_tonne_trucks:\n",
    "            df_trucks_needed.loc[cluster, '18-tonne HGV (24)'] = 2     \n",
    "\n",
    "    # Add a row to the DataFrame that sums the \n",
    "    # number of trucks needed for each truck type.\n",
    "    df_trucks_needed.loc['Total'] = df_trucks_needed.sum()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Return the DataFrame with the truck allocation for each cluster. \n",
    "    return df_trucks_needed"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fefc7037",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# "

   "source": [
    "# Create a column to identify the day of the week that the order was dispatched.\n",
    "kite_nonDX['weekday'] = kite_nonDX['DateDespatched'].apply(lambda x: x.weekday())\n",
    "\n",
    "# Remove orders from the DataFrame that were dispatched on a Saturday (5) or Sunday (6).    \n",
    "kite_nonDX = kite_nonDX.loc[\n",
    "            ~((kite_nonDX['weekday'] == 5)|(kite_nonDX['weekday'] == 6))]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Check this has worked.\n",
    "kite_nonDX['weekday'].unique()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1706df4d",

    "#### Minimum Daily Pallets. "
   ]

  {

   "source": [
    "To determine the trucks needed in each cluster, we will use our truck_allocation() function. The number of pallets we will input into this function is the minimum number of pallets to be delivered in a single day for each cluster. The rationale for using the minimum number of daily pallets was to minimise financial risk by only committing to the number of pallets that Kite is almost certainly guaranteed to have to deliver."
   ]

    "#### Median Daily Pallets. "

    "We will now look at a different strategy.\n",

   "source": [
    "Now that we had two strategies for truck allocation, we needed to compare them by calculating their cost savings for Kite. To calculate their cost savings, we created a function to generate models based on pallet numbers. While our exploratory model worked, it had limitations as it only delivered the minimum number of pallets, rather than fill the truck allocated to those pallets, thereby missing potential cost savings. After interim feedback, we decided as a group to refine our calculation and create a new function. "
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0817ef7f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Our exploratory model can be seen below. It had limitations and so it is commented out. Its main limitation was that it did not compute the cost savings of using the total truck capacity in each cluster, rather it assumed that the number of pallets being delivered is the same each day."
   ]

    "# # Function to calculate the cost savings of a particular truck allocation model\n",
    "\n",
    "# def cost_savings(model):\n",
    "   \n",
    "#     # First working out the cost of the trucks in each cluster:\n",
    "    \n",
    "#     # Defining the running and standing costs for each truck type\n",
    "#     standing_costs_3_5_tonne_van = 600\n",
    "#     standing_costs_7_5_tonne_LGV = 1250\n",
    "#     standing_costs_18_tonne_HGV = 1800\n",
    "#     running_costs_3_5_tonne_van = 2800\n",
    "#     running_costs_7_5_tonne_LGV = 3200\n",
    "#     running_costs_18_tonne_HGV = 3600\n",
    "   \n",
    "#     # Creating a copy of the model \n",
    "#     truck_costs = model\n",
    "   \n",
    "#     # Adding columns to store the running and standing costs for the trucks in each cluster\n",

    "#     truck_costs['18_tonne_standing_costs'] = (truck_costs['18-tonne HGV (24)']*\n",

    "\n",
    "#     # Now working out the total pallets and delivery costs for each cluster   \n",
    "    \n",
    "#     # Checking the total number of pallets delivered currently and delivery costs spent,\n",
    "#     # per cluster\n",
    "#     pallet_cost_now = kite_nonDX.groupby('Cluster Label')[['Pallets','DeliveryCost']].sum()\n",
    "\n",
    "#     # We need to scale the pallet and cost numbers to a calendar month\n",
    "#     # Divide the cost numbers by 18 (number of working days in the data) \n",
    "#     # and multiply by 22 (number of working days in a month)\n",
    "#     pallet_cost_now['Pallets'] = pallet_cost_now['Pallets']/18*22\n",
    "#     pallet_cost_now['DeliveryCost'] = pallet_cost_now['DeliveryCost']/18*22\n",
    "   \n",
    "   \n",
    "\n",
    "#     # Joining the two DataFrames (truck_costs and pallet_cost_now)\n",
    "\n",
    "#     df_cost_savings = pallet_cost_now.join(truck_costs, how = 'inner', rsuffix = '_right')\n",

    "#     df_cost_savings = df_cost_savings.drop(columns = 'Pallets_right')\n",

    "#     df_cost_savings['Courier Cost per Pallet (Current)']=(df_cost_savings['DeliveryCost']/\n",

    "#                      df_cost_savings['Pallets'])*100\n",
    "\n",
    "#     # Calculating cost saving £, note this is for the calendar month\n",
    "#     df_cost_savings['cost saving £'] = (df_cost_savings['Courier Cost (Current)'] -\n",

    "#     # Add a total row\n",
    "#     df_cost_savings.append(df_cost_savings.sum(numeric_only=True), ignore_index=True).round(1)\n",

    "#     df_cost_savings['cost saving %'] = (df_cost_savings['cost saving £']/\n",
    "#                                         df_cost_savings['Courier Cost (Current)'])*100\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#     # Returning the DataFrame with the cost saving information\n",
    "#     return df_cost_savings.round(1) "

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4f8ca7a8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Our refined model, that accounted for the cost savings when using the capacity of the trucks allocated, can be seen below. This is the one we used for our cost analysis. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "id": "5e00c0f7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Function to calculate the cost savings of a particular truck allocation model\n",
    "\n",
    "def cost_savings(model):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Looking at the number of pallets delivered each day for each cluster\n",
    "    pallets_day = kite_nonDX.pivot_table(index='Cluster Label', \n",
    "                                         columns='DateDespatched',\n",
    "                                         values='Pallets',\n",
    "                                         aggfunc='sum').transpose()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Using a for loop to work out the number of pallets that can be delivered each day in each cluster\n",
    "    # Using the model to define the truck capacity in each cluster\n",
    "    for cluster in range(0,5):\n",
    "        capacity = ((model.loc[cluster, '3.5-tonne Van (2)']*2) + \n",
    "                    (model.loc[cluster, '7.5-tonne LGV (14)']*14) + \n",
    "                    (model.loc[cluster, '18-tonne HGV (24)']*24))\n",
    "        pallets_day.iloc[:, cluster] = (pallets_day.iloc[:, cluster].apply(\n",
    "                                        lambda x : capacity if x > capacity else x))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Summing the pallets that can be delivered by trucks in each cluster\n",
    "    Pallets_truck = pallets_day.sum()\n",
    "    # Scaling this up to a month\n",
    "    Pallets_truck_month = Pallets_truck*22/18\n",
    "    # Storing this information in a DataFrame\n",
    "    Pallets_truck_month_df = Pallets_truck_month.to_frame()\n",
    "    # Changing column names to be more appropriate\n",
    "    Pallets_truck_month_df = Pallets_truck_month_df.rename(\n",
    "                                columns={0: 'Pallets delivered by in-house trucks'})\n",
    "        \n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Now working out the cost of the trucks in each cluster:\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Defining the running and standing costs for each truck type\n",
    "    standing_costs_3_5_tonne_van = 600\n",
    "    standing_costs_7_5_tonne_LGV = 1250\n",
    "    standing_costs_18_tonne_HGV = 1800\n",
    "    running_costs_3_5_tonne_van = 2800\n",
    "    running_costs_7_5_tonne_LGV = 3200\n",
    "    running_costs_18_tonne_HGV = 3600\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Creating a copy of the model \n",
    "    truck_costs = model\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Adding columns to store the running and standing costs for the trucks in each cluster\n",
    "    truck_costs['3.5_tonne_standing_costs'] = (truck_costs['3.5-tonne Van (2)']*\n",
    "                                               standing_costs_3_5_tonne_van)\n",
    "    truck_costs['7.5_tonne_standing_costs'] = (truck_costs['7.5-tonne LGV (14)']*\n",
    "                                               standing_costs_7_5_tonne_LGV)\n",
    "    truck_costs['18_tonne_standing_costs'] = (truck_costs['18-tonne HGV (24)']*\n",
    "                                              standing_costs_18_tonne_HGV)\n",
    "    truck_costs['3.5_tonne_running_costs'] = (truck_costs['3.5-tonne Van (2)']*\n",
    "                                              running_costs_3_5_tonne_van)\n",
    "    truck_costs['7.5_tonne_running_costs'] = (truck_costs['7.5-tonne LGV (14)']*\n",
    "                                              running_costs_7_5_tonne_LGV)\n",
    "    truck_costs['18_tonne_running_costs'] = (truck_costs['18-tonne HGV (24)']*\n",
    "                                             running_costs_18_tonne_HGV)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Adding a column to store the total truck costs for each cluster\n",
    "    truck_costs['Total_costs_month'] = truck_costs.iloc[:,5:10].sum(axis=1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Removing columns we don't need\n",
    "    truck_costs = truck_costs[['Pallets', 'Total_costs_month']]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Now working out the total pallets and delivery costs for each cluster   \n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Checking the total number of pallets delivered currently and delivery costs spent, per cluster\n",
    "    pallet_cost_now = (kite_nonDX.groupby('Cluster Label')[['Pallets',\n",
    "                                                            'DeliveryCost']].sum())\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Scale the pallet and cost numbers to a business month. \n",
    "    # Divide the cost numbers by 18 (number of working days in the data) \n",
    "    # and multiply by 22 (number of working days in a month)\n",
    "    pallet_cost_now['Pallets'] = pallet_cost_now['Pallets']/18*22\n",
    "    pallet_cost_now['DeliveryCost'] = pallet_cost_now['DeliveryCost']/18*22\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Joining the two DataFrames (truck_costs and pallet_cost_now)\n",
    "    df_cost_savings = pallet_cost_now.join(truck_costs, how = 'inner', rsuffix = '_right')\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Removing unnecessary columns \n",
    "    df_cost_savings = df_cost_savings.drop(columns = 'Pallets_right')\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Calculating the courier cost per pallet \n",
    "    df_cost_savings['Courier Cost per Pallet (Current)'] = (df_cost_savings['DeliveryCost']/\n",
    "                                                            df_cost_savings['Pallets'])\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Concatenating df_cost_savings and Pallets_truck_month_df \n",
    "    df_cost_savings = pd.concat([df_cost_savings, Pallets_truck_month_df], axis=1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Renaming columns\n",
    "    df_cost_savings.rename(columns={'DeliveryCost': 'Courier Cost (Current)', \n",
    "                     'Total_costs_month': 'in-house trucks cost',\n",
    "                     'Pallets_Month':'Pallets delivered by in-house trucks'}, inplace=True)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Calculating the remaining pallets left to deliver by third-party couriers\n",
    "    df_cost_savings['Remaining Pallets'] = (df_cost_savings['Pallets']-\n",
    "                                            df_cost_savings['Pallets delivered by in-house trucks'])\n",
    "    # Calculating the cost to deliver these remaining pallets with third-party couriers\n",
    "    df_cost_savings['Courier Cost Remaining Pallets'] = \\\n",
    "                                        (df_cost_savings['Courier Cost per Pallet (Current)']*\n",
    "                                        df_cost_savings['Remaining Pallets'])\n",
    "    # Calculating the total cost of implementing this partial replacement model\n",
    "    df_cost_savings['Partial Replacement Model Total Cost'] = \\\n",
    "                                        (df_cost_savings['in-house trucks cost']+\n",
    "                                        df_cost_savings['Courier Cost Remaining Pallets'])\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Calcuate the % of total pallets delivered using in-house trucks\n",
    "    df_cost_savings['Pallets delivered by in-house trucks, % total'] = \\\n",
    "                                        (df_cost_savings['Pallets delivered by in-house trucks']/\n",
    "                                        df_cost_savings['Pallets']*100)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Calculate cost saving £, note this is for the calendar month\n",
    "    df_cost_savings['cost saving £'] = (df_cost_savings['Courier Cost (Current)'] - \n",
    "                                        df_cost_savings['Partial Replacement Model Total Cost'])\n",
    "    df_cost_savings['cost saving %'] = (df_cost_savings['cost saving £']/\n",
    "                                        df_cost_savings['Courier Cost (Current)'])*100\n",
    "\n",
    "    return df_cost_savings.round()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "929544de",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# "
   ]

   ]

       "  <tbody>\n",

    "Model 2 leads to an overall increase in the number and size of the fleet, with four out of five clusters requiring extra capacity. While this obviously represents an additional monthly fleet investment, it leads to an increase in cost savings in three of the five clusters. This is particularly evident in Cluster 1 (Birmingham), where the cost saving jumps to 20%, fulfilling Kite’s original need to save 20% on delivery costs around the Coventry distribution centre."
